</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Quantitative imaging is the analysis of retrieved numeric data from images with the goal of reducing subjective assessment. It is an increasingly important radiologic tool to assess treatment response in oncology patients. Quantification of response to therapy depends on the tumor type and method of treatment. Anatomic imaging biomarkers that quantify liver tumor response to cytotoxic therapy are based on temporal change in the size of the tumors. Anatomic biomarkers have been incorporated into the World Health Organization criteria and the Response Evaluation Criteria in Solid Tumors (RECIST) versions 1.0 and 1.1. However, the development of novel therapies with different mechanisms of action, such as antiangiogenesis or radioembolization, has required new methods for measuring response to therapy. This need has led to development of tumor- or therapy-specific guidelines such as the Modified CT Response Evaluation (Choi) Criteria for gastrointestinal stromal tumors, the European Association for Study of the Liver (EASL) criteria, and modified RECIST for hepatocellular carcinoma, among many others. The authors review the current quantification criteria used in the evaluation of treatment response in liver tumors, summarizing their indications, advantages, and disadvantages, and discuss future directions with newer methods that have the potential for assessment of treatment response. Knowledge of these quantitative methods is important to facilitate pivotal communication between oncologists and radiologists about cancer treatment, with benefit ultimately accruing to the patient.</div><div role="paragraph">© RSNA, 2013</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.336135511">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.336135511">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig01" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135511/asset/images/large/135511fig01.jpeg" height="2060" width="3000" aria-labelledby="fig01" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span> Current and evolving oncologic imaging biomarkers as they apply to assessment of treatment response. The anatomic criteria are based on tumor size reduction and are best applied for cytotoxic therapies. The functional criteria are based on specific tumors and therapy. Molecular criteria such as PERCIST are tumor dependent and apply to fluorodeoxyglucose (FDG)–avid cancers. Many evolving imaging biomarkers are being evaluated for specific tumors and treatment options and remain to be validated. <i>DWI</i> = diffusion-weighted imaging, <i>EASL</i> = European Association for Study of the Liver, <i>irRC</i> = Immune-related Response Criteria, <i>MRE</i> = magnetic resonance (MR) elastography, <i>mRECIST</i> = modified RECIST, <i>MRS</i> = MR spectroscopy, <i>PERCIST</i> = Positron Emission Tomography Response Criteria in Solid Tumors, <i>RECICL</i> = Response Evaluation Criteria in Cancer of the Liver, <i>RECIST</i> = Response Evaluation Criteria in Solid Tumors, <i>WHO</i> = World Health Organization.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135511&amp;id=fig01">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig02a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135511/asset/images/large/135511fig02a.jpeg" height="889" width="847" aria-labelledby="fig02a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span> High-grade sarcoma in a 63-year-old woman with a liver metastasis. Axial contrast-enhanced computed tomographic (CT) images show the difference between the WHO criteria <b>(a)</b> and RECIST <b>(b)</b>. The WHO criteria are based on the sum of the areas (white cross) of all measured lesions; RECIST emphasizes the sum of the longest diameters (white line) of a limited number of target measurable lesions.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135511&amp;id=fig02a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig02b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135511/asset/images/large/135511fig02b.jpeg" height="889" width="828" aria-labelledby="fig02b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span> High-grade sarcoma in a 63-year-old woman with a liver metastasis. Axial contrast-enhanced computed tomographic (CT) images show the difference between the WHO criteria <b>(a)</b> and RECIST <b>(b)</b>. The WHO criteria are based on the sum of the areas (white cross) of all measured lesions; RECIST emphasizes the sum of the longest diameters (white line) of a limited number of target measurable lesions.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135511&amp;id=fig02b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig03" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135511/asset/images/large/135511fig03.jpeg" height="739" width="899" aria-labelledby="fig03" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3</span> Multiple hepatic metastases from colorectal cancer in a 66-year-old man. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows several metastases, the largest of which has irregular ill-defined margins, nearly coalescent with other lesions, which can affect accuracy and reproducibility of quantification. In this case, it is better to choose smaller lesions (arrows) as the target ones for quantifying tumor response.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135511&amp;id=fig03">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig04a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135511/asset/images/large/135511fig04a.jpeg" height="732" width="935" aria-labelledby="fig04a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span> Multiple hepatic metastases from colorectal carcinoma in a 55-year-old man. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images illustrate the difference between tumor measurements with RECIST 1.0 <b>(a)</b> and RECIST 1.1 <b>(b)</b>. In the RECIST 1.0 system <b>(a)</b>, a maximum of 10 target lesions per patient are measured, with a maximum of five per organ. In the RECIST 1.1 system <b>(b)</b>, a maximum of five target lesions per patient are measured, with a maximum of two per organ.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135511&amp;id=fig04a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig04b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135511/asset/images/large/135511fig04b.jpeg" height="732" width="939" aria-labelledby="fig04b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span> Multiple hepatic metastases from colorectal carcinoma in a 55-year-old man. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images illustrate the difference between tumor measurements with RECIST 1.0 <b>(a)</b> and RECIST 1.1 <b>(b)</b>. In the RECIST 1.0 system <b>(a)</b>, a maximum of 10 target lesions per patient are measured, with a maximum of five per organ. In the RECIST 1.1 system <b>(b)</b>, a maximum of five target lesions per patient are measured, with a maximum of two per organ.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135511&amp;id=fig04b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig05a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135511/asset/images/large/135511fig05a.jpeg" height="842" width="838" aria-labelledby="fig05a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span> Hepatic metastasis from colorectal cancer in a 62-year-old man. <b>(a, b)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT images obtained before <b>(a)</b> and after <b>(b)</b> bevacizumab therapy demonstrate a slight decrease in lesion size and a morphologic change from a heterogeneous lesion with irregular borders to a homogeneous hypoattenuating mass with sharp margins. <b>(c)</b> Posttreatment coronal FDG PET/CT fused image illustrates the lack of metabolic activity in the hepatic metastasis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135511&amp;id=fig05a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig05b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135511/asset/images/large/135511fig05b.jpeg" height="842" width="839" aria-labelledby="fig05b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span> Hepatic metastasis from colorectal cancer in a 62-year-old man. <b>(a, b)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT images obtained before <b>(a)</b> and after <b>(b)</b> bevacizumab therapy demonstrate a slight decrease in lesion size and a morphologic change from a heterogeneous lesion with irregular borders to a homogeneous hypoattenuating mass with sharp margins. <b>(c)</b> Posttreatment coronal FDG PET/CT fused image illustrates the lack of metabolic activity in the hepatic metastasis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135511&amp;id=fig05b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig05c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135511/asset/images/large/135511fig05c.jpeg" height="853" width="850" aria-labelledby="fig05c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5c</span> Hepatic metastasis from colorectal cancer in a 62-year-old man. <b>(a, b)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT images obtained before <b>(a)</b> and after <b>(b)</b> bevacizumab therapy demonstrate a slight decrease in lesion size and a morphologic change from a heterogeneous lesion with irregular borders to a homogeneous hypoattenuating mass with sharp margins. <b>(c)</b> Posttreatment coronal FDG PET/CT fused image illustrates the lack of metabolic activity in the hepatic metastasis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135511&amp;id=fig05c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig06a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135511/asset/images/large/135511fig06a.jpeg" height="759" width="837" aria-labelledby="fig06a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span> Hepatic metastasis from GIST treated with imatinib in a 51-year-old woman. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images obtained before <b>(a)</b> and 6 months after <b>(b)</b> therapy illustrate a 44% reduction in lesion attenuation, measuring 58.3 HU <b>(a)</b> and 32.7 HU <b>(b)</b>. This finding is consistent with a partial response to therapy. Lesion attenuation was measured by placing an ROI within the lesion (white circle).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135511&amp;id=fig06a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig06b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135511/asset/images/large/135511fig06b.jpeg" height="759" width="838" aria-labelledby="fig06b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span> Hepatic metastasis from GIST treated with imatinib in a 51-year-old woman. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images obtained before <b>(a)</b> and 6 months after <b>(b)</b> therapy illustrate a 44% reduction in lesion attenuation, measuring 58.3 HU <b>(a)</b> and 32.7 HU <b>(b)</b>. This finding is consistent with a partial response to therapy. Lesion attenuation was measured by placing an ROI within the lesion (white circle).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135511&amp;id=fig06b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig07a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135511/asset/images/large/135511fig07a.jpeg" height="870" width="850" aria-labelledby="fig07a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span> Hepatocellular carcinoma in a 58-year-old man who underwent <sup>90</sup>Y radioembolization of the right hepatic lobe. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images illustrate the difference in measurements based on EASL criteria and on modified RECIST. <b>(a)</b> Pretreatment image demonstrates multiple hepatocellular carcinomas. <b>(b)</b> On a posttreatment image, quantification of residual viable tumor in the largest lesion is shown by using EASL criteria (black lines). <b>(c)</b> On the same posttreatment image as <b>b</b>, the longest diameter of the enhancing residual tumor is measured (black line), with care taken to avoid any major intervening areas of necrosis as specified by modified RECIST.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135511&amp;id=fig07a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig07b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135511/asset/images/large/135511fig07b.jpeg" height="812" width="838" aria-labelledby="fig07b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span> Hepatocellular carcinoma in a 58-year-old man who underwent <sup>90</sup>Y radioembolization of the right hepatic lobe. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images illustrate the difference in measurements based on EASL criteria and on modified RECIST. <b>(a)</b> Pretreatment image demonstrates multiple hepatocellular carcinomas. <b>(b)</b> On a posttreatment image, quantification of residual viable tumor in the largest lesion is shown by using EASL criteria (black lines). <b>(c)</b> On the same posttreatment image as <b>b</b>, the longest diameter of the enhancing residual tumor is measured (black line), with care taken to avoid any major intervening areas of necrosis as specified by modified RECIST.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135511&amp;id=fig07b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig07c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135511/asset/images/large/135511fig07c.jpeg" height="812" width="836" aria-labelledby="fig07c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7c</span> Hepatocellular carcinoma in a 58-year-old man who underwent <sup>90</sup>Y radioembolization of the right hepatic lobe. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images illustrate the difference in measurements based on EASL criteria and on modified RECIST. <b>(a)</b> Pretreatment image demonstrates multiple hepatocellular carcinomas. <b>(b)</b> On a posttreatment image, quantification of residual viable tumor in the largest lesion is shown by using EASL criteria (black lines). <b>(c)</b> On the same posttreatment image as <b>b</b>, the longest diameter of the enhancing residual tumor is measured (black line), with care taken to avoid any major intervening areas of necrosis as specified by modified RECIST.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135511&amp;id=fig07c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig08a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135511/asset/images/large/135511fig08a.jpeg" height="794" width="837" aria-labelledby="fig08a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span> Hepatic metastasis from melanoma in an 83-year-old man who underwent ipilimumab immunotherapy. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images obtained before <b>(a)</b> and 4 months after <b>(b)</b> therapy show that the edges of the lesion are better defined after treatment and that the lesion area (black lines) has decreased from 5.3 cm<sup>2</sup> to 2.3 cm<sup>2</sup> (a 56% decrease), findings that correspond to partial response and that should be confirmed 4 weeks later.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135511&amp;id=fig08a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig08b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135511/asset/images/large/135511fig08b.jpeg" height="794" width="838" aria-labelledby="fig08b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span> Hepatic metastasis from melanoma in an 83-year-old man who underwent ipilimumab immunotherapy. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images obtained before <b>(a)</b> and 4 months after <b>(b)</b> therapy show that the edges of the lesion are better defined after treatment and that the lesion area (black lines) has decreased from 5.3 cm<sup>2</sup> to 2.3 cm<sup>2</sup> (a 56% decrease), findings that correspond to partial response and that should be confirmed 4 weeks later.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135511&amp;id=fig08b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig09a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135511/asset/images/large/135511fig09a.jpeg" height="755" width="837" aria-labelledby="fig09a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span> GIST in a 46-year-old man with multiple hepatic metastases treated with imatinib. <b>(a, b)</b> Pretreatment axial CT image <b>(a)</b> demonstrates multiple hepatic metastases that appear hypermetabolic in the FDG PET/CT image <b>(b)</b>. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial CT image obtained at 8-month follow-up <b>(c)</b> shows a decrease in the number and size of the liver lesions, findings consistent with partial response. However, the correlative FDG PET/CT image <b>(d)</b> shows resolution of hypermetabolic liver lesions, indicative of complete response.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135511&amp;id=fig09a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig09b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135511/asset/images/large/135511fig09b.jpeg" height="756" width="837" aria-labelledby="fig09b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span> GIST in a 46-year-old man with multiple hepatic metastases treated with imatinib. <b>(a, b)</b> Pretreatment axial CT image <b>(a)</b> demonstrates multiple hepatic metastases that appear hypermetabolic in the FDG PET/CT image <b>(b)</b>. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial CT image obtained at 8-month follow-up <b>(c)</b> shows a decrease in the number and size of the liver lesions, findings consistent with partial response. However, the correlative FDG PET/CT image <b>(d)</b> shows resolution of hypermetabolic liver lesions, indicative of complete response.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135511&amp;id=fig09b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig09c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135511/asset/images/large/135511fig09c.jpeg" height="754" width="838" aria-labelledby="fig09c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9c</span> GIST in a 46-year-old man with multiple hepatic metastases treated with imatinib. <b>(a, b)</b> Pretreatment axial CT image <b>(a)</b> demonstrates multiple hepatic metastases that appear hypermetabolic in the FDG PET/CT image <b>(b)</b>. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial CT image obtained at 8-month follow-up <b>(c)</b> shows a decrease in the number and size of the liver lesions, findings consistent with partial response. However, the correlative FDG PET/CT image <b>(d)</b> shows resolution of hypermetabolic liver lesions, indicative of complete response.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135511&amp;id=fig09c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig09d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135511/asset/images/large/135511fig09d.jpeg" height="754" width="837" aria-labelledby="fig09d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9d</span> GIST in a 46-year-old man with multiple hepatic metastases treated with imatinib. <b>(a, b)</b> Pretreatment axial CT image <b>(a)</b> demonstrates multiple hepatic metastases that appear hypermetabolic in the FDG PET/CT image <b>(b)</b>. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial CT image obtained at 8-month follow-up <b>(c)</b> shows a decrease in the number and size of the liver lesions, findings consistent with partial response. However, the correlative FDG PET/CT image <b>(d)</b> shows resolution of hypermetabolic liver lesions, indicative of complete response.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135511&amp;id=fig09d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135511/asset/images/large/135511fig10a.jpeg" height="735" width="836" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span> Hepatocellular carcinoma in a 65-year-old man who underwent TARE, followed by TACE. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial CT images show a hepatic lesion with heterogeneous distribution of necrosis (*), ethiodized oil (arrow) and residual tumor (arrowhead) in the arterial phase <b>(a)</b>, which demonstrates washout in the equilibrium phase <b>(b)</b>. <b>(c)</b> Colorized map shows the distribution of viable tumor (pink), necrosis (orange), and ethiodized oil (blue). <b>(d)</b> Volumetric image illustrates the complex nonspherical shape of the whole lesion and its different components.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135511&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135511/asset/images/large/135511fig10b.jpeg" height="735" width="838" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span> Hepatocellular carcinoma in a 65-year-old man who underwent TARE, followed by TACE. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial CT images show a hepatic lesion with heterogeneous distribution of necrosis (*), ethiodized oil (arrow) and residual tumor (arrowhead) in the arterial phase <b>(a)</b>, which demonstrates washout in the equilibrium phase <b>(b)</b>. <b>(c)</b> Colorized map shows the distribution of viable tumor (pink), necrosis (orange), and ethiodized oil (blue). <b>(d)</b> Volumetric image illustrates the complex nonspherical shape of the whole lesion and its different components.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135511&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135511/asset/images/large/135511fig10c.jpeg" height="770" width="836" aria-labelledby="fig10c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10c</span> Hepatocellular carcinoma in a 65-year-old man who underwent TARE, followed by TACE. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial CT images show a hepatic lesion with heterogeneous distribution of necrosis (*), ethiodized oil (arrow) and residual tumor (arrowhead) in the arterial phase <b>(a)</b>, which demonstrates washout in the equilibrium phase <b>(b)</b>. <b>(c)</b> Colorized map shows the distribution of viable tumor (pink), necrosis (orange), and ethiodized oil (blue). <b>(d)</b> Volumetric image illustrates the complex nonspherical shape of the whole lesion and its different components.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135511&amp;id=fig10c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135511/asset/images/large/135511fig10d.jpeg" height="1139" width="838" aria-labelledby="fig10d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10d</span> Hepatocellular carcinoma in a 65-year-old man who underwent TARE, followed by TACE. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial CT images show a hepatic lesion with heterogeneous distribution of necrosis (*), ethiodized oil (arrow) and residual tumor (arrowhead) in the arterial phase <b>(a)</b>, which demonstrates washout in the equilibrium phase <b>(b)</b>. <b>(c)</b> Colorized map shows the distribution of viable tumor (pink), necrosis (orange), and ethiodized oil (blue). <b>(d)</b> Volumetric image illustrates the complex nonspherical shape of the whole lesion and its different components.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135511&amp;id=fig10d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135511/asset/images/large/135511fig11a.jpeg" height="726" width="839" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span> Hepatocellular carcinoma in a 51-year-old man who underwent <sup>90</sup>Y radioembolization. <b>(a)</b> Pretreatment axial CT image in the late arterial phase shows an avidly enhanced hepatic lesion, with only small foci of nonenhancement. <b>(b)</b> On an axial CT image 1 month after treatment, the lesion area is heterogeneously enhanced, with large areas of necrosis (arrow) with intervening viable tumor tissue (arrowheads). There is no change in tumor size. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial images show significant change in the volume of necrosis (red area). The pretreatment necrosis volume was 0.49 mL (0.7% of the whole lesion) <b>(c)</b>, but 1 month after treatment the necrosis volume increased to 18.3 mL (24.8% of the entire lesion) <b>(d)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135511&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135511/asset/images/large/135511fig11b.jpeg" height="726" width="836" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span> Hepatocellular carcinoma in a 51-year-old man who underwent <sup>90</sup>Y radioembolization. <b>(a)</b> Pretreatment axial CT image in the late arterial phase shows an avidly enhanced hepatic lesion, with only small foci of nonenhancement. <b>(b)</b> On an axial CT image 1 month after treatment, the lesion area is heterogeneously enhanced, with large areas of necrosis (arrow) with intervening viable tumor tissue (arrowheads). There is no change in tumor size. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial images show significant change in the volume of necrosis (red area). The pretreatment necrosis volume was 0.49 mL (0.7% of the whole lesion) <b>(c)</b>, but 1 month after treatment the necrosis volume increased to 18.3 mL (24.8% of the entire lesion) <b>(d)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135511&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135511/asset/images/large/135511fig11c.jpeg" height="671" width="841" aria-labelledby="fig11c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11c</span> Hepatocellular carcinoma in a 51-year-old man who underwent <sup>90</sup>Y radioembolization. <b>(a)</b> Pretreatment axial CT image in the late arterial phase shows an avidly enhanced hepatic lesion, with only small foci of nonenhancement. <b>(b)</b> On an axial CT image 1 month after treatment, the lesion area is heterogeneously enhanced, with large areas of necrosis (arrow) with intervening viable tumor tissue (arrowheads). There is no change in tumor size. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial images show significant change in the volume of necrosis (red area). The pretreatment necrosis volume was 0.49 mL (0.7% of the whole lesion) <b>(c)</b>, but 1 month after treatment the necrosis volume increased to 18.3 mL (24.8% of the entire lesion) <b>(d)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135511&amp;id=fig11c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135511/asset/images/large/135511fig11d.jpeg" height="671" width="834" aria-labelledby="fig11d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11d</span> Hepatocellular carcinoma in a 51-year-old man who underwent <sup>90</sup>Y radioembolization. <b>(a)</b> Pretreatment axial CT image in the late arterial phase shows an avidly enhanced hepatic lesion, with only small foci of nonenhancement. <b>(b)</b> On an axial CT image 1 month after treatment, the lesion area is heterogeneously enhanced, with large areas of necrosis (arrow) with intervening viable tumor tissue (arrowheads). There is no change in tumor size. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial images show significant change in the volume of necrosis (red area). The pretreatment necrosis volume was 0.49 mL (0.7% of the whole lesion) <b>(c)</b>, but 1 month after treatment the necrosis volume increased to 18.3 mL (24.8% of the entire lesion) <b>(d)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135511&amp;id=fig11d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135511/asset/images/large/135511fig12a.jpeg" height="728" width="838" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span> Hepatocellular carcinoma treated with <sup>90</sup>Y radioembolization in a 73-year-old woman with a cirrhotic liver. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial MR image <b>(a)</b> and diffusion-weighted image <b>(b)</b> obtained before treatment demonstrate a hypervascular lesion (arrow) with a small amount of necrosis in segment VIII and no significant diffusion restriction evident with the diffusion-weighted sequence <b>(b)</b>, with an ADC value of 1.0 × 10<sup>−3</sup> mm<sup>2</sup>/sec. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial MR image <b>(c)</b> and diffusion-weighted image <b>(d)</b> obtained in the arterial phase 45 days after treatment demonstrate a decrease in lesion size (arrow) and new foci of necrosis. Increase in the ADC value to 1.6 × 10<sup>−3</sup> mm<sup>2</sup>/sec suggests good tumor response <b>(d)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135511&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135511/asset/images/large/135511fig12b.jpeg" height="728" width="837" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span> Hepatocellular carcinoma treated with <sup>90</sup>Y radioembolization in a 73-year-old woman with a cirrhotic liver. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial MR image <b>(a)</b> and diffusion-weighted image <b>(b)</b> obtained before treatment demonstrate a hypervascular lesion (arrow) with a small amount of necrosis in segment VIII and no significant diffusion restriction evident with the diffusion-weighted sequence <b>(b)</b>, with an ADC value of 1.0 × 10<sup>−3</sup> mm<sup>2</sup>/sec. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial MR image <b>(c)</b> and diffusion-weighted image <b>(d)</b> obtained in the arterial phase 45 days after treatment demonstrate a decrease in lesion size (arrow) and new foci of necrosis. Increase in the ADC value to 1.6 × 10<sup>−3</sup> mm<sup>2</sup>/sec suggests good tumor response <b>(d)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135511&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135511/asset/images/large/135511fig12c.jpeg" height="739" width="839" aria-labelledby="fig12c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12c</span> Hepatocellular carcinoma treated with <sup>90</sup>Y radioembolization in a 73-year-old woman with a cirrhotic liver. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial MR image <b>(a)</b> and diffusion-weighted image <b>(b)</b> obtained before treatment demonstrate a hypervascular lesion (arrow) with a small amount of necrosis in segment VIII and no significant diffusion restriction evident with the diffusion-weighted sequence <b>(b)</b>, with an ADC value of 1.0 × 10<sup>−3</sup> mm<sup>2</sup>/sec. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial MR image <b>(c)</b> and diffusion-weighted image <b>(d)</b> obtained in the arterial phase 45 days after treatment demonstrate a decrease in lesion size (arrow) and new foci of necrosis. Increase in the ADC value to 1.6 × 10<sup>−3</sup> mm<sup>2</sup>/sec suggests good tumor response <b>(d)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135511&amp;id=fig12c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135511/asset/images/large/135511fig12d.jpeg" height="739" width="836" aria-labelledby="fig12d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12d</span> Hepatocellular carcinoma treated with <sup>90</sup>Y radioembolization in a 73-year-old woman with a cirrhotic liver. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial MR image <b>(a)</b> and diffusion-weighted image <b>(b)</b> obtained before treatment demonstrate a hypervascular lesion (arrow) with a small amount of necrosis in segment VIII and no significant diffusion restriction evident with the diffusion-weighted sequence <b>(b)</b>, with an ADC value of 1.0 × 10<sup>−3</sup> mm<sup>2</sup>/sec. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial MR image <b>(c)</b> and diffusion-weighted image <b>(d)</b> obtained in the arterial phase 45 days after treatment demonstrate a decrease in lesion size (arrow) and new foci of necrosis. Increase in the ADC value to 1.6 × 10<sup>−3</sup> mm<sup>2</sup>/sec suggests good tumor response <b>(d)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135511&amp;id=fig12d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135511/asset/images/large/135511fig13a.jpeg" height="735" width="837" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span> Hepatocellular carcinoma treated with TACE in a 52-year-old man with a cirrhotic liver. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced MR images obtained before <b>(a)</b> and 1 month after <b>(b)</b> therapy demonstrate no change in tumor size or vascularity. <b>(c, d)</b> <sup>31</sup>P MR spectroscopy spectra produced on a 3.0-T system before <b>(c)</b> and 1 month after <b>(d)</b> therapy show a decrease in the phosphodiesters <i>(PDE)</i> as well as an increase in the phosphomonoesters <i>(PME)</i> (arrows), with consequent increase in the phosphomonoester/phosphodiester ratio after therapy, a finding indicative of a poor response. α-<i>ATP</i> = alpha–adenosine triphosphate, β-<i>ATP</i> = beta–adenosine triphosphate, γ-<i>ATP</i> = gamma–adenosine triphosphate, <i>PCr</i> = phosphocreatine, <i>Pi</i> = inorganic phosphate.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135511&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135511/asset/images/large/135511fig13b.jpeg" height="735" width="837" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span> Hepatocellular carcinoma treated with TACE in a 52-year-old man with a cirrhotic liver. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced MR images obtained before <b>(a)</b> and 1 month after <b>(b)</b> therapy demonstrate no change in tumor size or vascularity. <b>(c, d)</b> <sup>31</sup>P MR spectroscopy spectra produced on a 3.0-T system before <b>(c)</b> and 1 month after <b>(d)</b> therapy show a decrease in the phosphodiesters <i>(PDE)</i> as well as an increase in the phosphomonoesters <i>(PME)</i> (arrows), with consequent increase in the phosphomonoester/phosphodiester ratio after therapy, a finding indicative of a poor response. α-<i>ATP</i> = alpha–adenosine triphosphate, β-<i>ATP</i> = beta–adenosine triphosphate, γ-<i>ATP</i> = gamma–adenosine triphosphate, <i>PCr</i> = phosphocreatine, <i>Pi</i> = inorganic phosphate.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135511&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135511/asset/images/large/135511fig13c.jpeg" height="651" width="824" aria-labelledby="fig13c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13c</span> Hepatocellular carcinoma treated with TACE in a 52-year-old man with a cirrhotic liver. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced MR images obtained before <b>(a)</b> and 1 month after <b>(b)</b> therapy demonstrate no change in tumor size or vascularity. <b>(c, d)</b> <sup>31</sup>P MR spectroscopy spectra produced on a 3.0-T system before <b>(c)</b> and 1 month after <b>(d)</b> therapy show a decrease in the phosphodiesters <i>(PDE)</i> as well as an increase in the phosphomonoesters <i>(PME)</i> (arrows), with consequent increase in the phosphomonoester/phosphodiester ratio after therapy, a finding indicative of a poor response. α-<i>ATP</i> = alpha–adenosine triphosphate, β-<i>ATP</i> = beta–adenosine triphosphate, γ-<i>ATP</i> = gamma–adenosine triphosphate, <i>PCr</i> = phosphocreatine, <i>Pi</i> = inorganic phosphate.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135511&amp;id=fig13c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135511/asset/images/large/135511fig13d.jpeg" height="651" width="851" aria-labelledby="fig13d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13d</span> Hepatocellular carcinoma treated with TACE in a 52-year-old man with a cirrhotic liver. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced MR images obtained before <b>(a)</b> and 1 month after <b>(b)</b> therapy demonstrate no change in tumor size or vascularity. <b>(c, d)</b> <sup>31</sup>P MR spectroscopy spectra produced on a 3.0-T system before <b>(c)</b> and 1 month after <b>(d)</b> therapy show a decrease in the phosphodiesters <i>(PDE)</i> as well as an increase in the phosphomonoesters <i>(PME)</i> (arrows), with consequent increase in the phosphomonoester/phosphodiester ratio after therapy, a finding indicative of a poor response. α-<i>ATP</i> = alpha–adenosine triphosphate, β-<i>ATP</i> = beta–adenosine triphosphate, γ-<i>ATP</i> = gamma–adenosine triphosphate, <i>PCr</i> = phosphocreatine, <i>Pi</i> = inorganic phosphate.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135511&amp;id=fig13d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135511/asset/images/large/135511fig14a.jpeg" height="892" width="785" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span> Dysplastic nodule in segment V of the liver in a 61-year-old man with cirrhosis. <b>(a–c)</b> T2-weighted MR image <b>(a)</b> demonstrates a slightly hypointense T2 signal within the dysplastic nodule (arrow), compared with a hyperintense signal on the T1-weighted image obtained before contrast material injection <b>(b)</b> and no arterial enhancement on the postcontrast image <b>(c)</b>. <b>(d)</b> Axial image from MR elastography demonstrates that the dysplastic nodule has lower stiffness (green), compared with the adjacent cirrhotic liver parenchyma (red).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135511&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135511/asset/images/large/135511fig14b.jpeg" height="892" width="790" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span> Dysplastic nodule in segment V of the liver in a 61-year-old man with cirrhosis. <b>(a–c)</b> T2-weighted MR image <b>(a)</b> demonstrates a slightly hypointense T2 signal within the dysplastic nodule (arrow), compared with a hyperintense signal on the T1-weighted image obtained before contrast material injection <b>(b)</b> and no arterial enhancement on the postcontrast image <b>(c)</b>. <b>(d)</b> Axial image from MR elastography demonstrates that the dysplastic nodule has lower stiffness (green), compared with the adjacent cirrhotic liver parenchyma (red).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135511&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135511/asset/images/large/135511fig14c.jpeg" height="939" width="785" aria-labelledby="fig14c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14c</span> Dysplastic nodule in segment V of the liver in a 61-year-old man with cirrhosis. <b>(a–c)</b> T2-weighted MR image <b>(a)</b> demonstrates a slightly hypointense T2 signal within the dysplastic nodule (arrow), compared with a hyperintense signal on the T1-weighted image obtained before contrast material injection <b>(b)</b> and no arterial enhancement on the postcontrast image <b>(c)</b>. <b>(d)</b> Axial image from MR elastography demonstrates that the dysplastic nodule has lower stiffness (green), compared with the adjacent cirrhotic liver parenchyma (red).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135511&amp;id=fig14c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135511/asset/images/large/135511fig14d.jpeg" height="939" width="790" aria-labelledby="fig14d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14d</span> Dysplastic nodule in segment V of the liver in a 61-year-old man with cirrhosis. <b>(a–c)</b> T2-weighted MR image <b>(a)</b> demonstrates a slightly hypointense T2 signal within the dysplastic nodule (arrow), compared with a hyperintense signal on the T1-weighted image obtained before contrast material injection <b>(b)</b> and no arterial enhancement on the postcontrast image <b>(c)</b>. <b>(d)</b> Axial image from MR elastography demonstrates that the dysplastic nodule has lower stiffness (green), compared with the adjacent cirrhotic liver parenchyma (red).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135511&amp;id=fig14d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Llovet JM, Ricci S, Mazzaferro V, et al. Sorafenib in advanced hepatocellular carcinoma. <em>N Engl J Med</em> 2008;359(4):378–390.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1056/NEJMoa0708857">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18650514/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Sorafenib+in+advanced+hepatocellular+carcinoma&amp;author=JM+Llovet&amp;author=S+Ricci&amp;author=V+Mazzaferro&amp;publication_year=2008&amp;journal=N+Engl+J+Med&amp;pages=378-390&amp;doi=10.1056%2FNEJMoa0708857&amp;pmid=18650514">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Figueiras RG, Padhani AR, Goh VJ, et al. Novel oncologic drugs: what they do and how they affect images. <em>RadioGraphics</em> 2011;31(7):2059–2091.</d